[recv] {"type": "message_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Analyzing testing constraints**\n\nI’m noticing there might not be a native run for the tests, and I’m curious if they can be headless. The build includes awt_xawt, but it seems we don’t necessarily need to run it. I'm thinking about how the dynamic access report could be generated during compile time, which would record reachable call sites. The execution of JVM tests seems essential here for coverage, especially on a headless machine. I should explore using public APIs, but there are restrictions with the native calls. Reflecting on how to handle certain classes, I might be able to use Unsafe instead.\n\n**Assessing dynamic call lines**\n\nI’m thinking dynamic call lines need a displayable Window object. I wonder if I could avoid the displayable requirement by adding a hierarchy listener and not running until an event is triggered. I might try calling setWindowAlpha with a custom Component, but it expects a Window. I could instantiate a Window and override methods to say it's displayable, but that's tricky due to constructor issues. Alternatively, maybe I could use Unsafe to allocate an instance without a constructor. There are limitations on obtaining Unsafe, and I'm weighing various approaches for window construction without throwing errors.\n\n**Investigating call sites**\n\nI’m considering how call sites are seen if methods are reachable. It seems that some uncovered lines are still present, which makes me think that making the Mac runnable method reachable through static analysis might resolve the issue. I'm pondering if the native image report on uncovered call sites comes from call site coverage instrumentation. We really need to execute at runtime. Perhaps I could create a test class with the same name, but I'm not sure. Maybe using JNA's Mac utilities via a public API by setting os.name could help as well.\n\n**Exploring testing options**\n\nI'm considering testing alternatives without using mock dependencies. Maybe I could think about external tools? However, I've noticed that Mockito generates subclasses through dynamic class loading, which isn't native-compatible. So, that's a bit tricky. Could Xvfb be useful in the continuous integration environment? It seems tests normally run in Docker, so I might need to look into setting up xvfb in that context. I should check the build details further!", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_08df50df848489740169f9691efc388197a77f54ccd0512f2d\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp-WkrpqOMdl9Mc7U9crdTf9qdAeNCJvPVeF5yg-n3tfKG0UIewmOcLVSknXKnAyVk_xgN4wDWqiC-we-M6jcklsrwApwJAmcCv7z5td67aNDrIvfqKOhO2JL2eyKse5nVeb6G08svyUY3IViPwlRAyjdmR1b9v2-37TY3HFplhanHt4A2ebOXNcJH5GdnjZsarnSmxUs5LAvlf8erTyGEvnqL3iPpyeVb6UIggYcG_IkGmLvtG8oG5B-EQd_nPgD-2kNq2t4egxoPZrQB8L1GQfi3eCc7R7w3f5SVxuaDDAAbnBKwWTAkmg8WGqsRhLsW0gFOPsp7qPcqiupUtXuvHQhfjZD2JTgoPBAZeRXPxQX4liX51H0-6vgh1NKmgUUZW6HDdjjAEOy79Fo5cQFGCCEjU3EFDMR5Fk4uztkg2w1BBoBPVFv0NUxAORJtEBq5darY4FVp6-um_qAFvjKqo31ZWJYAKz43rdzJZ_aZG8ji1XPUhSyUOINJno4V864x0ribRJx39tImUtci0VwOXHWWEbib3oLXz9W1MLEW9THSbDHV2gZNidnzsjl0yY6rVJXEYU3onM5TcbxVEPLTHHlfvZLOxeSYUF5OUpItHGJzwxJchKg8LMjAsKnmemsthe__vKGb-q3P6MZt-UzpJFvzbLhTyFVXpnWzzYckVVnzac-iCY-6_ZZAcUs5-IZw7p_UuIDIQ4_YJslBDB7-7oTvNc4puihc_PmuFDoJEaRcvJeWBhRXNpUFabwlvvRXLwi6SkIB9mS0bNQfgi_XimMGUPnmizC8fgLIhhHtaMRtZCRS8bSE6GhBn2bEzhuWMas2ns4-l1pCXcuHlKDqw_HCYtZAUIFj8Idg3GFr__7ZLLKgzQreamkp2Y3VthHio4AlGVy8EAR-X_waSZ-cs38IiDo8SyaHIuMcvWGp3BFpbwdeRM2_hUzn22r10s0FH5x2Ux-8sCgerAOsPY1Wq1noT1fhlJQDrZIrTOrVUPOKa10UKI8JFs1ETb_eSoq2iYCPRnMypP92tOPL3zQPL9TZADH9pKZz5lBj2u-jbS2r_zcLGQrV3cvyWiPXcBwd4qaTCclRp-V4ExyTiZzong06mtotWFMIq2S0SK_boynDaRSQmaTk83Ip6TJexsTwYDyFtYP34KgBjK20pFEDmoupcT0HkYJJEcEsvumstv_xG_iBeidpHPPw-VtKzcu-6MT5dl1YP4HQ_mi4hPu899WOsU9b1RC4Jg3xYrRg1L-tB5gpWYWi0FF-BX4uowKSF_lp9dvD7wEMla4KNMlgwlh5Z3FFYLfxrT8hdGL21tbxXtE8QcOZMJEwxHaJhkqwp14LMzyZPf4Qb4e8OpnVEbmbUiOVE9liImBxa7QGBsl_lPCgWn1d